" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="0">https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/3EwwVTo9#0</div></p>
<p>If you look closely at move 61-62, you'll see how two 2300 players missed a mate in 1 in a classical game. Yes, we were down to 30 seconds, but still, how?<br>One aspect of mutual blindness is both players trusting each other and not testing the last moves for obvious mistakes. Another aspect is seeing a pawn that you could take with check on f5, more tempting than a mate in this case :) Before that on move 59 I blundered the pawn, not seeing that after Bxe3 Qd7 white is winning a second pawn. This becomes a lot more explainable when we consider that black has been defending passively for thirty moves by that point, in a quite depressing position which only has two possible outcomes which didn't excite me. The pressure mounted on both the position and the clock, until I let my guard down. To paraphrase Chekhov, any player can handle a crisis, it's move-to-move problems that wear you out.</p>
<p>Here are some photos from these tournaments, which kept me motivated despite some horrific blunders.</p>
