<hr />
<h3><a href="84VpVCDn#hallucination-blunders" id="hallucination-blunders"></a><strong>Hallucination blunders</strong></h3>
<p>Have you ever hallucinated that a piece had already been captured when it hasn't? Or perhaps you thought your bishop on a2 could capture on f6 in some line? Counted on phantom pieces in lines where they've already left several moves ago? If the answer is no, don't lie to yourself :) We're all susceptible to tricks that the mind plays on us, and nobody's visualization is perfect, including World Champions. Their hallucinations are just further down the line...</p>
<p><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;blog on blunders: Ivanov, Mike - Watson, John&quot;]
[Site &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/1fV7BWHa&quot;]
[Date &quot;2015.08.01&quot;]
[White &quot;Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Black &quot;Watson, John&quot;]
[Result &quot;1/2-1/2&quot;]
[Annotator &quot;Mikey&quot;]
[Variant &quot;Standard&quot;]
[ECO &quot;B40&quot;]
[Opening &quot;Sicilian Defense: French Variation, Westerinen Attack&quot;]
[StudyName &quot;blog on blunders&quot;]
[ChapterName &quot;Ivanov, Mike - Watson, John&quot;]
[Source &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/1fV7BWHa&quot;]
[Orientation &quot;white&quot;]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. g3 g5 7. Na3 g4 8. Nh4 Qg5 9. c4 Nc7 (9... Ndb4 10. Nb5 Nxe5 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 b5) 10. f4 gxf3 11. Nxf3 Qf5 12. Qe2 Bg7 13. Bg2 d5 14. O-O Qh5 15. Rae1 O-O 16. Nc2 Bd7 17. Ne3 f6 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Bxf6 Rxf6 20. h3 Raf8 21. Ng4 Rf5 22. Nh4 (22. Nfe5 Nxe5 (22... Be8 23. Nd7)) 22... Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 24. Qxf1 Ne8 25. Qf4 Kg7 26. Nf3 dxc4 27. Nge5 Nxe5 28. Nxe5 Bc6 29. g4 Qh4 30. Qf7+ (30. Bxc6 bxc6 (30... Qe1+ 31. Kh2 bxc6 (31... Qe2+) 32. Qf7+) 31. Qf7+ Kh6) 30... Kh6 31. Qf8+ Kg5 32. Qe7+ Nf6 33. Qxe6 Be4 34. Bxe4?? Qe1+ 35. Kg2 Qxd2+ 36. Kg1 Qc1+ 37. Kg2 Qd2+ { 1/2-1/2  wins. } 1/2-1/2

" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="58">https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/1fV7BWHa#58</div><br>In this position I got really excited because I thought I saw a forced mate; 30. Qf7+ Kh6, Qf8+ Kg5, Qe7+ Nf6, Qg7+ Kf4, Nd3+ Kg3, Qc7+ e5 Qxe5#<br>Only once I got to the Qg7 check did I realize there's a problem, the pawn on c4 is black instead of white so Nd3+ is not a move...This shows another important part of blunders, weird geometry. We're used to the c4 pawn being white instead of black here, which is why our mind deceives us. The most famous example of this was the mate in 1 that Kramnik missed against Deep Fritz, because the white knight was on f8, not its usual stable.</p>
<p>For another example of weird geometry, can you guess how black blundered in the next game?<br><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;blog on blunders: Ivanov, Mike - Itkin, David&quot;]
[Site &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/ghF5x8Kz&quot;]
[Date &quot;2017.01.16&quot;]
[White &quot;Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Black &quot;Itkin, David&quot;]
[Result &quot;1-0&quot;]
[Variant &quot;Standard&quot;]
[ECO &quot;B52&quot;]
[Opening &quot;Sicilian Defense: Moscow Variation, Main Line&quot;]
[Annotator &quot;https://lichess.org/@/theScot&quot;]
[StudyName &quot;blog on blunders&quot;]
[ChapterName &quot;Ivanov, Mike - Itkin, David&quot;]
[Source &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/ghF5x8Kz&quot;]
[Orientation &quot;black&quot;]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Qa4 (8. d4) 8... e6 9. Na3 Nf6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Bf4 Be7 12. Nxd4 O-O 13. Nxc6 Bxa3 14. Qxa3 Qxc6 15. Rad1 a6 16. Rd6 Qb5 17. Qb3 Qxb3 18. axb3 Nd5 19. Bg3 Rfd8 20. Rd1 Rxd6 21. Bxd6 f5 22. Be5 Kf7 23. c4 Nf6 24. Rd6 b5 25. cxb5 axb5 26. f3 Ra1+ 27. Kf2 Rc1 28. Rb6 Rc2+ 29. Kf1 Nd5 30. Rb7+ Kg6 31. Rxg7+ Kh6 32. Rg8 f4 33. Ke1 Kh5 34. g3 (34. Rg7 h6 35. Bd4 Ne3 36. g4+ Kh4 37. Rg6 Kh3 38. Bxe3 fxe3 39. Rxh6+ Kg2 40. Rf6 Kxh2 41. g5 Rg2 42. Rxe6 Rxg5 43. Re4 Rg1+ 44. Ke2 Rb1 45. Kxe3) 34... Rxh2 35. gxf4 Ne3 36. Re8 Nc2+ 37. Kf1 (37. Kd1 Ne3+ 38. Kc1 Rc2+) 37... Ne3+ 38. Ke1 (38. Kg1 Rg2+ 39. Kh1 Rf2) 38... Nc2+ 39. Kd1 Ne3+ 40. Kc1 Rc2+ 41. Kb1 Rc6 42. Rb8 Nf1 43. Bc3 Rc5 44. Rb6 Nh2 45. Rxe6 Nxf3 46. Bg7 Rc7 (46... Nd2+ 47. Ka2 Rc7 48. Bd4 Rc8) 47. Bc3 Kg4 48. Rh6 Kxf4 49. b4 Re7 50. Rh5 Rb7 51. Kc2 Kg4 52. Rh6 Kg5 53. Rh3 Kg4 54. Rh6 Nh4 55. Kd3 Nf5 56. Rh1 (56. Rf6 h5 57. Ke4 Ng3+ 58. Ke5 h4 59. Rg6+ Kh3 60. Rh6) 56... h5 57. Rg1+ Ng3 58. Be5 h4 59. Kd4 Rh7 60. Bb8 Kf3 61. Ra1 h3 62. Ra3+ Kf2 63. Bxg3+ Kg2 64. Kc5 Rh5+ 65. Kb6 Rg5 66. Bf4 Rg4 67. Bd6 Rg6 68. Kc5 Rg5+ 69. Kd4 Rg4+ 70. Kd5 Rg5+ 71. Ke6 Rg6+ 72. Ke7 Rh6 73. Re3 h2 74. Re2+ Kg1 75. Rxh2 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0

" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="121">https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/ghF5x8Kz#121</div><br>Having realized that the position was losing, I tried one last trick, based on weird geometry. With the help of the faraway bishop, the rook comes between the white pawns to save the day with Ra3+...</p>
<p>But if you thought that was bad, you ain't seen nothing yet:</p>
<p><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;blog on blunders: Latorre, Vincent - Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Site &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/ZfIj6xT6&quot;]
[Date &quot;2024.04.02&quot;]
[White &quot;Latorre, Vincent&quot;]
[Black &quot;Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Result &quot;0-1&quot;]
[Annotator &quot;Mikey&quot;]
[Variant &quot;Standard&quot;]
[ECO &quot;B01&quot;]
[Opening &quot;Scandinavian Defense: Marshall Variation&quot;]
[StudyName &quot;theScot's Study&quot;]
[ChapterName &quot;Latorre, Vincent - Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Source &quot;https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/PxtQqMs4&quot;]
[Orientation &quot;white&quot;]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Nxd5 4. c4 Nb6 5. Nc3 e5 6. d5 Bb4 7. Bd2 c6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Bg4 10. Nxe5 Bxe2 11. Nxe2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qe7 13. dxc6 Na6 14. cxb7 Rae8 15. c5 Nxc5 16. b8=Q Rxb8 17. Nc6 Qe4 (17... Qf6 18. Nxb8 Rd8 19. Nd7 Rxd7 20. Qe3 Nd3+ 21. Kf1 g6 22. Ng3 Nc4 23. Qe2 Rd4) (17... Nd3+ 18. Kf1 Qf6) 18. Nxb8 Nd3+ 19. Kf1 Nc4 20. Qg5 Re8 21. h4 Qxe2+ 22. Kg1 Rxb8 (22... Qxf2+ 23. Kh2 Nce5 24. Qg3 Qd4 25. Rhf1 Ng4+ 26. Kh1 Ndf2+) 23. Qg3 Re8 24. Kh2 Ncxb2 25. a4 h5 26. Rhf1 Nc4 27. f3 Re6 28. Qb8+ Kh7 29. Qb5 Rg6 30. Rg1 Nce5 31. Qd5 Qf2 32. Qe4 Qg3+ { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1

" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="33">https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/PxtQqMs4#33</div></p>
<p>After Nc6, I reached to put my knight on the d3 square, hovered my hand over the knight and then jerked myself back like a man who almost fell from a bridge...my opponent was visibly confused trying to figure out where my knight could go to when my queen was hanging. You see the problem is that when I calculated this variation, my mind's eye transferred the pin on the e2 knight onto the d2 queen! If the queen was pinned, then after Kf1 Qf6 Qxd3 Qxc6 I would indeed have a promising position. An important skill is recovering from blunders and my attack was dangerous enough that even after blundering I could still win, with a little help from my opponent.</p>
<hr />
<p class="img-container"><img src="https://image.lichess1.org/display?fmt=webp&amp;h=0&amp;op=resize&amp;path=ublogBody:wIuObhzWf5i0:khjCIOPq.jpg&amp;w=800&amp;sig=0d21b4ff42b466919b9f54ff171b9d045de1f229" alt="" /><br><img src="https://image.lichess1.org/display?fmt=webp&amp;h=0&amp;op=resize&amp;path=ublogBody:vHrlBcHDOgji:AN8YMe4J.jpg&amp;w=800&amp;sig=8b619f8da096e0f6cdfdf43039caf095dc93d25a" alt="" /><img src="https://image.lichess1.org/display?fmt=webp&amp;h=0&amp;op=resize&amp;path=ublogBody:2gbBjmyRYqcm:kMxkfy7j.jpg&amp;w=800&amp;sig=6e4f771a10024684325c89155f4ff90db8282ba9" alt="" /></p>
<hr />
<h3><a href="84VpVCDn#psychological-blunders" id="psychological-blunders"></a><strong>Psychological Blunders</strong></h3>
<p>Sometimes our mindsets become our downfall by leading us to blunders, for a plethora of reasons. Some players are overconfident and think any move will win. On the other hand, less confident players are scared of playing up and give their opponents too much respect, not capitalizing on blunders. When we're defending, we may want the suffering to end, trying to force our way out of positions that aren't forceable. The game below falls into that category:</p>
<p><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;blog on blunders: Rolando, Allarcon - Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Site &quot;https://lichess.org/study/KfnG3o4R/6dNL2M1K&quot;]
[Date &quot;2017.04.22&quot;]
[White &quot;Rolando, Allarcon&quot;]
[Black &quot;Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Result &quot;1-0&quot;]
[Annotator &quot;https://lichess.org/@/theScot&quot;]
[Variant &quot;Standard&quot;]
[ECO &quot;A45&quot;]
[Opening &quot;Trompowsky Attack&quot;]
[StudyName &quot;theScot's Study&quot;]
[ChapterName &quot;Rolando, Allarcon - Ivanov, Mike&quot;]
[Source &quot;https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/vmuQV2P8&quot;]
[Orientation &quot;white&quot;]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 Nc6 4. f3 Nf6 5. d5 e5 6. Bg3 Ne7 7. e4 Ng6 8. h4 Bc5 9. h5 Nxh5 10. Rxh5 Bxg1 11. Bxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5+ Kf8 13. Rh5 Qf6 14. c3 Qf4 15. Qd2 Be3 16. Qe2 d6 17. Kd1 g6 18. Rh1 Qg5 19. Na3 Kg7 20. Nc4 Bf4 21. Qf2 c6 22. Kc2 cxd5 23. Qd4+ Be5 24. Qxd5 Be6 25. Qd2 Bf4 26. Qd4+ Be5 27. Nxe5 dxe5 28. Qd2 Qxd2+ 29. Kxd2 Rad8+ 30. Ke3 Rd6 31. Be2 Rhd8 32. Rhd1 Rxd1 33. Bxd1 h5 34. Be2 Kf6 35. c4 Kg5 36. g3 f5 37. exf5 gxf5 38. f4+ Kf6 39. Rh1 Bf7 40. b3 exf4+ 41. gxf4 Rh8 42. Rh4 a5 43. Bf3 b6 44. Kd4 Rg8 45. Rh3 Rh8 46. Rh4 Rg8 47. Be2 Rg2 48. Bxh5 Bxh5 49. Rxh5 Kg6 50. Rh8 Rxa2 51. Rb8 Kh5 52. Rxb6 Kg4 53. c5 Kxf4 54. c6 Rc2 55. Kd5 Ke3 56. Rb7 f4 57. Re7+ Kd3 58. Rf7 Kc3 59. Rxf4 Kxb3 60. Rf8 Rd2+ 61. Kc5 Rc2+ 62. Kd5 Rd2+ 63. Kc5 Rc2+ 64. Kb5 a4 65. Rf3+ Ka2 66. Rf4 Rxc6 67. Kxc6 a3 68. Kb5 Kb2 69. Rf2+ Kb3 70. Rf3+ Kb2 71. Kb4 a2 72. Rf2+ Kb1 73. Kb3 a1=N+ 74. Kc3 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0

" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="131">https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/vmuQV2P8#131</div></p>
<p>I was playing for the FM title and only needed a draw, which was so close I could smell it. On top of that, it was hot and humid that August in Spain and my body was just telling me to get out of there, to escape the tension... After defending a pawn down rook endgame I only had to push a3 and the pawns would promote at the same time, for example ...a3 Rc4 Rxc4, Kxc4 Kb2, c7 a2, c8Q a1Q =. But wanting to be as forcing as possible, I took on c6, thinking that there's no way the king could get back in time to catch my pawn. This is true, but a knight in the corner doesn't fight well against rooks...A common strategy strong players use is get a slightly better position and let the weaker opponent sweat it out (literally in this case) until they find a way to lose the game even if it wasn't easy to begin with.</p>
<p>The trend of the game before the blunder has a large influence on the blunder itself. The best example is GM Santos resigning against GM Vallejo Pons in a position where his only legal move was easily winning:</p>
<p><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;Leon Masters&quot;]
[Site &quot;Leon ESP&quot;]
[Date &quot;2018.07.07&quot;]
[Round &quot;1.4&quot;]
[White &quot;Francisco Vallejo Pons&quot;]
[Black &quot;Jaime Santos Latasa&quot;]
[Result &quot;1-0&quot;]
[WhiteElo &quot;2707&quot;]
[BlackElo &quot;2576&quot;]
[Annotator &quot;https://lichess.org/@/theScot&quot;]
[Variant &quot;Standard&quot;]
[ECO &quot;E34&quot;]
[Opening &quot;Nimzo-Indian Defense: Classical Variation, Noa Variation&quot;]
