[ChapterName &quot;Francisco Vallejo Pons - Jaime Santos Latasa&quot;]
[Source &quot;https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/I6AfZcOf&quot;]
[Orientation &quot;white&quot;]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. e3 c5 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. f3 Qd6 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. Nf4 b6 12. Be2 Rd8 13. Rd1 Bb7 14. O-O Rac8 15. Qb2 Na5 16. Be1 Nd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bh4 Rf8 19. Bg3 Qe7 20. Rfe1 cxd4 21. cxd4 Nc4 22. Bxc4 Bxc4 23. e4 Qb7 24. h4 b5 25. a3 a5 26. Qd2 Qb6 27. Bf2 b4 28. d5 Qd6 29. axb4 axb4 30. dxe6 Qxe6 31. Qxb4 Rfd8 32. Kh2 h6 33. Bg3 Bd3 34. Rd2 Ba6 35. Red1 Rxd2 36. Rxd2 Bc4 37. Qb2 Qe7 38. Qd4 Be6 39. Rb2 Qc5 40. Be5 Qxd4 41. Bxd4 Rd8 42. Rb4 Rd7 43. h5 f5 44. e5 Bf7 45. Rb8+ Kh7 46. Bc5 Bxh5 47. e6 Rd2 48. e7 Re2 49. Kg1 Re5 50. Bb4 f4 51. Rf8 g5 52. Kh2 Re6 53. g4 fxg3+ 54. Kxg3 Re3 55. Bc5 Re5 56. Bd6 Re6 57. Bb4 Re2 58. Bd6 Re6 59. Bc5 Re5 60. Rc8 Re6 61. f4 gxf4+ 62. Kxf4 Kg7 63. Rf8 Kh7 64. Kf5 Re1 65. Bd4 Bg6+ 66. Kf6 Re4 67. Be5 Re2 68. Rh8+ { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0

" class="lpv--autostart is2d" data-ply="134">https://lichess.org/study/fjsRFHMu/I6AfZcOf#134</div></p>
<p>The trend of the game was white pressing positionally and materially for the vast majority of the game. Even at the end, where Vallejo played Rh8+?? He could have won with Ke6. Jaime either saw Ke6 or felt that this position should be losing, and was ready to resign even before Vallejo played a move, having mentally resigned already. Vallejo Pons on the other hand also felt that this should be winning, and didn't bother to check the details of his &quot;tactical conversion&quot;.</p>
<p>Lastly, we can blunder because we really don't want a draw, and our sense of danger gets squashed by our desire to win:</p>
<p><div data-pgn="[Event &quot;Skilling Open&quot;]
[Site &quot;chess24.com INT&quot;]
[Date &quot;2020.11.29&quot;]
[Round &quot;3.12&quot;]
